statement.p:
The partial derivative of f with respect to y at (a,b) is
\boxed{ f_y(a,b) = \frac{\partial f}{\partial y}(a,b) = \lim_{h\to0}\frac{f(a,b+h)-f(a,b)}{h}, }
when this limit exists.

Let
f:D\subseteq\mathbb R^3\to\mathbb R.
At a point (a,b,c),
\boxed{ f_x(a,b,c) = \lim_{h\to0} \frac{f(a+h,b,c)-f(a,b,c)}{h}, }
\boxed{ f_y(a,b,c) = \lim_{h\to0} \frac{f(a,b+h,c)-f(a,b,c)}{h}, }
and
\boxed{ f_z(a,b,c) = \lim_{h\to0} \frac{f(a,b,c+h)-f(a,b,c)}{h}, }
when the limits exist.

subsection.p:
Define
S(x,y)= \begin{cases} \dfrac{xy}{x^2+y^2}, & (x,y)\ne(0,0),\\[2mm] 0, & (x,y)=(0,0). \end{cases}
Compute the partial derivatives at the origin.
